addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> were reducible, say <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)=a(x)b(x)]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R[x]]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b(x)]]></fr:tex> are nonconstant polynomials. Reducing this equation modulo <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> and using the assumption on the coefficients of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>, we obtain the equation
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[x^{n}=\overline {a(x)b(x)}]]></fr:tex>
in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(R/P)[x]]]></fr:tex> where the bar denotes the polynomials with coefficients reduced modulo <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is a prime ideal, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R/P]]></fr:tex> is an integral domain (by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001F.xml"
addr="ra-001F"
title="Ideal is prime iff quotient ring is integral domain">Ideal is prime iff quotient ring is integral domain</fr:link>). Then both <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {a(x)}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {b(x)}]]></fr:tex> have 0 constant terms, i.e., the constant terms of both <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b(x)]]></fr:tex> belong to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>But then the constant term <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> may be written as the product of these two, which contradicts the hypothesis that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0}\notin  P^{2}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
