title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Proposition 9.4.13</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-000H.xml"
addr="ra-000H"
title="Integral domain">Integral domain</fr:link>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> be a formal variable. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\in  R[x]]]></fr:tex> be a (nonconstant) monic polynomial
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(x)=x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+…+a_{1}x+a_{0}.]]></fr:tex>
Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-001D.xml"
addr="ra-001D"
title="Prime Ideal">prime ideal</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Suppose for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j=1,…,n]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{j}\in  R]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0}\notin  P^{2}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible.</fr:p>
 
   
